@model gsend.pro.Models.MCodeModel
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <h3>@Model.Description</h3>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>@Model.MCode is used to send a command to an open COM port without blocking any commands and without waiting for a response.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <h3>@GSend.Language.Resources.WebMenuParameters</h3>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <table class="paramTable">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Name</th>
                    <th>Optional</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td>COM Port</td>
                    <td>No</td>
                    <td>Name of the COM port to be opened, i.e. COM2</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Command</td>
                    <td>No</td>
                    <td>Data to be sent to the COM port</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <h3>@GSend.Language.Resources.WebMenuUsage</h3>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>Data is sent to an open COM port as a string, it is up to the device connected to interperate the data and provide a response.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>Each @Model.MCode command must be on a line with no other commands.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>The name of the COM port must appear as the first parameter within the comment but on the same line.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>An error will be shown if the COM port does not exist or has not been opened.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>An error will be shown if the parameters of the @Model.MCode command are not correctly formatted.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>The parameters required are the COM port and the string data to be sent, parameters must be seperated by a colon (:).</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p><a href="/Home/Variables">Variables</a> can be used to ensure the line limit of 256 characters is not breached</p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <h3>@GSend.Language.Resources.WebMenuExample</h3>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
        <p>The following sample opens a COM port, sends a non blocking command and then closes the COM port, in this example the string "SETPINHIGH:A9" is the data sent to the com port.</p>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-12">
            <code>
                @Html.ToGCode(@"M620 ;COM9
M622;COM9:SETPINHIGH:A9
M621;COM9
.. other g code here
M30")
            </code>

            <p>The above example assumes that there is a custom program running on the port which can accept the string data sent.</p>
    </div>
</div>

@await Html.PartialAsync("~/Views/MCodes/_seeAlso.cshtml", Model)